Done. `ADR-001-notification-architecture.md` is written with a definitive recommendation for **Redis Streams**.

The core argument: given a 6-person team, no Kafka experience, existing Redis production infra, and a 2-week setup constraint, Redis Streams is the only option that satisfies all criteria. Kafka's exactly-once semantics are superficially attractive but don't deliver end-to-end guarantees without the same application-level idempotency Redis Streams would need — and Kafka's operational complexity is a real risk for a team this size.

Key technical properties cited in the trade-off:

| Property | Redis Streams | Kafka |
|---|---|---|
| Throughput (at 10× target) | ~5% of single-node capacity | Overkill |
| Exactly-once | Application-level dedup required | Same — no end-to-end guarantee |
| Message retention | `MAXLEN` (bounded) | Disk-based, configurable |
| Consumer groups | `XREADGROUP` + PEL + `XCLAIM` | Group coordinator + rebalance protocol |
| Setup time | 3–5 days | 3–4 weeks minimum |
| Ops burden (6-person team) | Near-zero (existing infra) | Cluster management, tuning, monitoring |
